<subSubSection box="[151,870,1680,1707]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,1680,2016]" box="[151,870,1680,1707]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,284,1680,1706]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Etymology</emphasis>
. Greek, 
<emphasis box="[385,464,1681,1706]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">mikros</emphasis>
, small, 
<emphasis box="[556,667,1681,1706]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">pedetikos</emphasis>
, good at leaping.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,1680,2016]" box="[197,727,1719,1746]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,342,1719,1745]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Dimensions</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[356,542,1719,1745]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Male &amp; female</emphasis>
. Up to 
<quantity box="[630,723,1720,1746]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" unit="mm" value="3.2">3.2 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,1680,2016]" lastBlockId="30.[151,1436,152,912]" lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Head wider than pronotum. Vertex produced in front, 1.0–1.5 times as long medially as length next to eyes; vertex rounded to face; frontal region shagreen, disc smooth. Face usually unmarked, clypeus sometimes with feint horizontal arcs; clypellus broad (1.5 times as long as wide), slightly tapering, not extending beyond lower margin of gena. Gena obtusely emarginate. Profemur with very short setae in row AV, about 
<specimenCount box="[229,386,1913,1939]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="intercalary">8 intercalary</specimenCount>
setae and one AM1 seta. Protibial setal formula 1+4, mesotibial setal formula 4+4, mesofemur setal formula 2+2+1, middle pair of subequal length, distal seta longest. Tegmina with 4 apical and 3 anteapical cells, outer cell of variable size, costal vein yellow-orange, other veins and cells transparent; appendix reduced. Hind wing normal in macropterous specimens, and in submacropterous female specimens, hind wing about half as long as tegmina; with jugal lobe folded over anal area in both cases. Ocelli marginal; ocellus separated from adjacent eye by 1.6 times its diameter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,152,912]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,457,267,293]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Abdominal apodeme</emphasis>
. Produced posteriorly, anterior and posterior apodeme extending into sternite I and II respectively (
<figureCitation box="[334,501,306,332]" captionStart="FIGURES 274–283" captionStartId="54.[151,271,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[217,1364,243,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-74@54.[183,1404,194,1939]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 274–283. Micropedeticus ochrus. Fig. 274, abdominal apodeme, posterior; Fig. 275, abdominal apodeme, anterior; Fig. 276, aedeagus, dorsal view; Fig. 277, aedeagus, lateral view; Fig. 278, connective; Fig. 279, plate and valve; Fig. 280, pygofer, dorsal view; Fig. 281, pygofer, lateral view; Fig. 282, style; Fig. 283, sternite VII, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5321556" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5321556/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Figs 274, 275</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,152,912]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,395,344,370]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Genital capsule</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[412,476,344,370]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Male</emphasis>
. Aedeagus symmetrical, linear in dorsal view; apex forked, recurved ventrally. Connective with arms fused, (
<figureCitation box="[511,616,384,410]" captionStart="FIGURES 274–283" captionStartId="54.[151,271,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[217,1364,243,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-74@54.[183,1404,194,1939]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 274–283. Micropedeticus ochrus. Fig. 274, abdominal apodeme, posterior; Fig. 275, abdominal apodeme, anterior; Fig. 276, aedeagus, dorsal view; Fig. 277, aedeagus, lateral view; Fig. 278, connective; Fig. 279, plate and valve; Fig. 280, pygofer, dorsal view; Fig. 281, pygofer, lateral view; Fig. 282, style; Fig. 283, sternite VII, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5321556" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5321556/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 278</figureCitation>
). Plate triangular, apex rounded. Valve narrow. Pygofer lobe acutely triangular, apex blunt, laterally setose (
<figureCitation box="[609,712,422,448]" captionStart="FIGURES 274–283" captionStartId="54.[151,271,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[217,1364,243,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-74@54.[183,1404,194,1939]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 274–283. Micropedeticus ochrus. Fig. 274, abdominal apodeme, posterior; Fig. 275, abdominal apodeme, anterior; Fig. 276, aedeagus, dorsal view; Fig. 277, aedeagus, lateral view; Fig. 278, connective; Fig. 279, plate and valve; Fig. 280, pygofer, dorsal view; Fig. 281, pygofer, lateral view; Fig. 282, style; Fig. 283, sternite VII, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5321556" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5321556/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 281</figureCitation>
); ventrally opposable, in repose, closure is effected by plates, with overlapping ventral flap of pygofer lobes. Anal tube short, recessed less than half-way into pygofer; tergite X well sclerotized, internally produced into a frame-work articulating with dorsal apodeme of aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[274,440,538,564]" captionStart="FIGURES 274–283" captionStartId="54.[151,271,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[217,1364,243,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-74@54.[183,1404,194,1939]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 274–283. Micropedeticus ochrus. Fig. 274, abdominal apodeme, posterior; Fig. 275, abdominal apodeme, anterior; Fig. 276, aedeagus, dorsal view; Fig. 277, aedeagus, lateral view; Fig. 278, connective; Fig. 279, plate and valve; Fig. 280, pygofer, dorsal view; Fig. 281, pygofer, lateral view; Fig. 282, style; Fig. 283, sternite VII, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5321556" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5321556/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Figs 280, 281</figureCitation>
). Style differentiated into apophysis, preapical lobe, anterior and medial lobes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,152,912]" box="[197,1182,576,603]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,390,576,602]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Genital capsule</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[404,495,576,602]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Female</emphasis>
. Sternite VII posterior margin broadly rounded (
<figureCitation box="[1066,1169,577,603]" captionStart="FIGURES 274–283" captionStartId="54.[151,271,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[217,1364,243,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-74@54.[183,1404,194,1939]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 274–283. Micropedeticus ochrus. Fig. 274, abdominal apodeme, posterior; Fig. 275, abdominal apodeme, anterior; Fig. 276, aedeagus, dorsal view; Fig. 277, aedeagus, lateral view; Fig. 278, connective; Fig. 279, plate and valve; Fig. 280, pygofer, dorsal view; Fig. 281, pygofer, lateral view; Fig. 282, style; Fig. 283, sternite VII, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5321556" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5321556/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 283</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,152,912]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,368,615,641]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Relationships</emphasis>
. This genus is a typical member of the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1908" box="[905,1047,616,642]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Paralimnini">Paralimnini</taxonomicName>
. No known member of this tribe has similarly enlarged abdominal apodemes. The aedeagus with its apical spines is a character that occurs in a number of genera in this tribe, such as 
<taxonomicName authority="Linnavuori" authorityName="Linnavuori" authorityYear="1959" box="[609,838,693,719]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Afrosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[609,697,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Afrosus</emphasis>
Linnavuori
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Theron" authorityName="Theron" authorityYear="1980" box="[851,1093,693,719]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Platentomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[851,997,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Platentomus</emphasis>
Theron
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Theron" authorityName="Theron" authorityYear="1973" box="[1105,1266,693,719]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Ragia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1105,1175,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Ragia</emphasis>
Theron
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Davies. These" authorityName="Davies. These" authorityYear="1988" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Restiobia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1325,1436,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Restiobia</emphasis>
Davies. These
</taxonomicName>
genera could be considered distant relatives. 
<taxonomicName authority="Theron" authorityName="Theron" authorityYear="1975" box="[877,1122,732,758]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Cedarotettix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[877,1026,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Cedarotettix</emphasis>
Theron
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Vilbaste" authorityName="Vilbaste" authorityYear="1969" box="[1182,1436,732,758]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hengchunia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1182,1328,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Hengchunia</emphasis>
Vilbaste
</taxonomicName>
also have the shaft bearing apical or subapical spines, but have additional basal paraphyses. Similarities in colouration, size and shape are found in some undescribed species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Theron (Theron, 1975)" authorityName="Theron (Theron" authorityYear="1975" box="[974,1385,809,835]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pravistylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[974,1106,809,834]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Pravistylus</emphasis>
Theron (
<bibRefCitation author="Theron" box="[1215,1377,809,835]" firstAuthor="Theron" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="189 - 206" refId="ref38231" refString="Theron, J. G. (1975) The Naude species of South African Cicadellidae (Hemiptera). IV. Species assigned to the genera Aconura Lethierry and Deltocephalus Burmeister. Journal of the Entomological Society of Southern Africa, 38 (2), 189 - 206." type="journal article" year="1975">Theron, 1975</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Lindberg (Stiller, 1998)" authorityName="Lindberg (Stiller" authorityYear="1998" box="[151,549,848,874]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Nicolaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,257,848,873]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Nicolaus</emphasis>
Lindberg (
<bibRefCitation author="Stiller" box="[391,541,848,874]" firstAuthor="Stiller" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="325 - 364" refId="ref38168" refString="Stiller, M. (1998) The African leafhopper genus Nicolaus Lindberg (Homoptera: Cicadellidae: Paralimnini). African Entomology, 6 (2), 325 - 364." type="journal article" year="1998">Stiller, 1998</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and with 
<taxonomicName box="[671,882,848,873]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Theronus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="priapus" status="gen.n.">
<emphasis box="[671,882,848,873]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Theronus priapus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[891,967,847,873]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[891,967,847,873]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" rank="genus">gen.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
&amp; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1008,1062,849,873]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">sp.n.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1078,1218,848,874]" captionStart="FIGURES 47–50" captionStartId="44.[151,272,1235,1259]" captionTargetBox="[165,1429,198,1170]" captionTargetId="figure-62@44.[132,1462,148,1243]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURES 47–50. Theronus priapus and Lecacis species, habitus views. Fig. 47, T. priapus sp.n., male; Fig. 48, T. priapus, female brachypter; Fig. 49, T. priapus, female macropter; Fig. 50, L. platypennis Theron, male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5321540" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5321540/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Figs 47–49</figureCitation>
), but these genera have totally different genitalia.
</paragraph>
